Introduction¶

This dataset which is the Ford GoBike System Data, includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area for the month of February 2019.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There were 183412 entries and 16 columns in the dataset, but after cleaning there was 174952 entries and 20 columns. Most features are numeric in nature, with three categorical features which are the member gender, weekday, and user type.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in figuring out how the trip duration varies with respect to other features in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I expect that age and gender will have the strongest effect on the trip duration from the start to end stations. I also think that the user type will also play a major role, due to the experience of subscribers to customers.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, investigation of the distributions of individual variables is being carried out. I'll start by looking at the distribution of the main variable of interest: duration_sec.

How long does most trips take?¶

In [17]:
#starting with a standard-scaled plot of duration
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, trip_data['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6])
plt.hist(data = trip_data, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.title('Total trips duration')
plt.xlabel('Duration(sec)')
plt.ylabel('Total trips')
plt.xlim([-100,7000])
plt.show()

From the plot there is a long tail in the distribution so lets try with a log scale.

In [18]:
# plotting on a log scale instead
log_binsize = 0.02
bins = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(trip_data['duration_sec'].max())+log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[12, 6])
plt.hist(data = trip_data, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4, 2e4, 4e4, 8e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k', '40k', '80k'])
plt.title('Total trips duration')
plt.xlabel('Duration(sec)')
plt.ylabel('Total trips')
plt.show()

Observation¶

Duration has a long-tailed distribution, with most trips having durations on the low end, and few on the high end. When plotted on a log-scale, the duration distribution is unimodal and is slightly skewed right. The duration started at 200 with trips around 3000,with the peak between 500 and 700, then it falls gradually.

Lets look at the age feature

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The trip duration took on a large range of values, so I looked at the data using a log transform. Under the transformation, the data looked unimodal, with the peak between 500 and 700, and the plot was slightly skewed right.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

After cleaning the data extra features were extrated from the given features, to enhance our exploration on the dataset from more angles.

Observation¶

From the plot, duration had no correlation with age, but younger riders tend to stay longer on trips than the elderly riders.

Age plays a major role on the duration of the trip taken by the bikers. The elderly bikers do not spend much time on trips unlike the younger bikers who spend the most time.

Conclusions¶

The dataset did not have any duplicates but null values were present. After cleaning, extra features were extrated from the data to assist in the exploration and the following findings were derived at;

  1. Most people who go for rides are within the age range of 20-40 years.
  2. The male gender is more dominant in the bike trips.
  3. Most users are subcribers.
  4. Although subscribers are more, customers tend to go on longer trips.
  5. Most people go on bike rides on thursday, but they tend to stay longer on weekends.
